        <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-primary">3. Radical Honesty with Allies</h1>
        <p class="text-lg italic text-primary/80">"Always tell the truth to people there to help you"</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    
    <div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none">
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        Your lawyer, therapist, doctor, closest friends, financial advisor—these people can only help you to the 
        extent they understand your reality. Lying to them is like giving a surgeon false information before an 
        operation. The consequences compound over time, and the help you receive becomes not just ineffective but 
        potentially harmful because it's based on incomplete or false premises.
      </p>
      
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-base-content mt-8 mb-4">The Trust Equation in Professional Relationships</h3>
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        Professional helpers—lawyers, therapists, doctors, financial advisors—have seen everything. What shocks or 
        embarrasses you about your situation is likely routine for them. Your shame is costing you their expertise. 
        The fear of judgment from someone who's literally paid to be non-judgmental is perhaps the most expensive 
        form of self-sabotage.
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        Consider this: A therapist who doesn't know about your drinking problem can't help you develop healthy coping 
        mechanisms. A lawyer who doesn't know about your financial irregularities can't protect you from legal exposure. 
        A doctor who doesn't know about your recreational drug use might prescribe medication that creates dangerous 
        interactions. In each case, withholding information doesn't protect you—it exposes you to greater risk.
      </p>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-base-content mt-8 mb-4">The Psychology of Shame and Secrecy</h3>
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        Shame thrives in secrecy. When we hide aspects of our lives from people who could help, we're often protecting 
        an idealized version of ourselves that doesn't actually exist. This creates a double burden: not only do we 
        carry the weight of whatever we're hiding, but we also carry the exhausting cognitive load of maintaining 
        false narratives.
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        Research in psychology shows that secrets require constant mental energy to maintain. Every interaction with 
        the person you're hiding something from becomes a performance. This mental taxation reduces your cognitive 
        capacity for other tasks and decisions, making you less effective overall.
      </p>

      <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-primary/5 to-secondary/5 p-6 rounded-box border border-primary/20 backdrop-blur-sm mb-6">
        <h4 class="font-semibold text-primary mb-3">The Radical Honesty Framework:</h4>
        <ol class="text-base-content/70 text-sm space-y-2">
          <li><strong class="text-primary">1. Preparation:</strong> Write down what you're tempted to hide before the meeting</li>
          <li><strong class="text-primary">2. Early disclosure:</strong> Address difficult topics early in conversations, not late</li>
          <li><strong class="text-primary">3. Full context:</strong> Explain not just what happened, but why you made certain choices</li>
          <li><strong class="text-primary">4. Emotional honesty:</strong> Share how you feel about the situation, not just facts</li>
          <li><strong class="text-primary">5. Future focus:</strong> Discuss what you want to achieve, not just problems to solve</li>
        </ol>
      </div>

      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-base-content mt-8 mb-4">Case Study: The Executive Coach Revelation</h3>
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        Jennifer, a senior marketing director, hired an executive coach to help her advance to VP level. For six months, 
        they worked on presentation skills, leadership style, and strategic thinking. Despite the coaching, Jennifer 
        continued to struggle with team dynamics and wasn't getting promoted.
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        The breakthrough came when Jennifer finally revealed what she'd been hiding: she had severe social anxiety 
        that made team meetings and presentations genuinely terrifying experiences. She'd been managing it with alcohol 
        before important meetings and avoidance wherever possible.
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
        <strong>The Before:</strong> The coach was giving Jennifer advanced leadership techniques when she needed 
        basic anxiety management tools. They were working on executive presence when the real issue was clinical 
        anxiety requiring therapeutic intervention.
      </p>
      
      <p class="text-base-content/70 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
        <strong>The After:</strong> Once the coach understood the full picture, they connected Jennifer with appropriate 
        mental health resources, adjusted coaching techniques to work with her anxiety rather than against it, and 
        developed authentic leadership strategies that leveraged her natural strengths. Within eight months, Jennifer 
        was promoted to VP.
      </p>

